 absolute;left:-6.75%;top:.1em;font-family:Wingdings;font-size:90%'>n</span></span><span
 lang=EN-US style='color:#0033CC'>Father of Boolean algebra&#13;</span></span></div>
 <div style='mso-char-wrap:1;mso-kinsoku-overflow:1'><span style='position:
 absolute;top:22.5%;left:12.17%;width:63.67%;height:3.5%'><span
 style='font-size:67%'><span style='mso-special-format:bullet;color:#B2B2B2;
 mso-color-index:7;position:absolute;left:-5.88%;top:.1em;font-family:Wingdings;
 font-size:90%'>n</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>He came
 up with a type of linguistic algebra, the three </span></span><span
 style='position:absolute;top:26.0%;left:12.17%;width:59.36%;height:3.5%'><span
 lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>most basic operations of which were (and
 still are) </span></span><span style='position:absolute;top:29.5%;left:12.17%;
 width:62.17%;height:3.5%'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>AND, OR and
 NOT. It was these three functions that </span></span><span style='position:
 absolute;top:33.25%;left:12.17%;width:59.73%;height:3.5%'><span lang=EN-US
 style='font-size:67%'>formed the basis of his premise, and were the only </span></span><span
 style='position:absolute;top:36.75%;left:12.17%;width:64.41%;height:3.5%'><span
 lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>operations necessary to perform comparisons
 or basic </span></span><span style='position:absolute;top:40.25%;left:12.17%;
 width:55.43%;height:3.5%'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>mathematical
 functions. &#13;</span></span></div>
 <div style='mso-char-wrap:1;mso-kinsoku-overflow:1'><span style='position:
 absolute;top:44.5%;left:12.17%;width:63.67%;height:3.5%'><span
 style='font-size:67%'><span style='mso-special-format:bullet;color:#B2B2B2;
 mso-color-index:7;position:absolute;left:-5.88%;top:.1em;font-family:Wingdings;
 font-size:90%'>n</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>Boole’s
 system (detailed in his 'An Investigation of the </span></span><span
 style='position:absolute;top:48.25%;left:12.17%;width:55.43%;height:3.5%'><span
 lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>Laws of Thought, on Which Are Founded the </span></span><span
 style='position:absolute;top:51.75%;left:12.17%;width:58.98%;height:3.5%'><span
 lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>Mathematical Theories of Logic and
 Probabilities', </span></span><span style='position:absolute;top:55.25%;
 left:12.17%;width:66.29%;height:3.5%'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>1854)
 was based on a binary approach, processing only </span></span><span
 style='position:absolute;top:58.75%;left:12.17%;width:61.42%;height:3.5%'><span
 lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>two objects - the yes-no, true-false, on-off,
 zero-one </span></span><span style='position:absolute;top:62.5%;left:12.17%;
 width:55.43%;height:5.25%'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>approach.</span><span
 lang=EN-US> &#13;</span></span></div>
 <div style='mso-char-wrap:1;mso-kinsoku-overflow:1'><span style='position:
 absolute;top:68.5%;left:12.17%;width:56.36%;height:3.5%'><span
 style='font-size:67%'><span style='mso-special-format:bullet;color:#B2B2B2;
 mso-color-index:7;position:absolute;left:-6.64%;top:.1em;font-family:Wingdings;
 font-size:90%'>n</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>Surprisingly,
 given his standing in the academic </span></span><span style='position:absolute;
 top:72.0%;left:12.17%;width:56.17%;height:3.5%'><span lang=EN-US
 style='font-size:67%'>community, Boole's idea was either criticized or </span></span><span
 style='position:absolute;top:75.5%;left:12.17%;width:55.99%;height:3.5%'><span
 lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>completely ignored by the majority of his
 peers. &#13;</span></span></div>
 <div style='mso-char-wrap:1;mso-kinsoku-overflow:1'><span style='position:
 absolute;top:79.75%;left:12.17%;width:65.16%;height:3.5%'><span
 style='font-size:67%'><span style='mso-special-format:bullet;color:#B2B2B2;
 mso-color-index:7;position:absolute;left:-5.74%;top:.1em;font-family:Wingdings;
 font-size:90%'>n</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:67%'>Eventually,
 one bright student, Claude Shannon (1916-</span></span><span style='position:
